Turning from your gaze, it swims into the little coral fixture in the middle of its bowl to contemplate the awful breadth of human sin. Thereafter, whenever someone puts their face near its glass, it swims away, thudding fruitlessly into the opposite side of its bowl.

A curious mix of overfitting and words I've never typed out/phrases I've never used. HTC, you need to step up your machine learning game.

Like the one seeded from "L;" never once typed "baby," much less followed it with "girl!" Overfitting can be observed in a, b, c, d, t, and y, where the algorithm generates a particularly long phrase which reads like it was plagiarized. Additional phrase-loops crop up multiple times throughout the experiment, some of which are quite long. It is of note that the algorithm fails to find a follow-up for "xor," preferring instead to start from a previously observed sequence. It does this for at least several words starting with "X," and I have not found a counterexample.
